SIMPLE: tierce
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Tierce
<hw>Tierce</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>tierce</ets> a
third, from <ets>tiers</ets>, <ets>tierce</ets>, third, fr. L.
<ets>tertius</ets> the third; akin to <ets>tres</ets> three. See
<er>Third</er>, <er>Three</er>, and cf. <er>Terce</er>, <er>Tercet</er>,
<er>Tertiary</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A cask whose content is one
third of a pipe; that is, forty-two wine gallons; also, a liquid measure
of forty-two wine, or thirty-five imperial, gallons.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A cask larger than a barrel, and smaller than a
hogshead or a puncheon, in which salt provisions, rice, etc., are packed
for shipment.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>The third tone of the scale. See
<er>Mediant</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A sequence of three playing cards of the same suit.
Tierce of ace, king, queen, is called <xex>tierce-major</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Fencing)</fld> <def>A position in thrusting or
parrying in which the wrist and nails are turned downward.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(R. C. Ch.)</fld> <def>The third hour of the day, or
nine <sc>a. m,</sc>; one of the canonical hours; also, the service
appointed for that hour.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 1508 -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tierce</ent>⟦br⟧
